//purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhile Ibsen's plays were seldom performed in Romania in the first half of the 20th century, historical sources highlight his strong impact on the national theatre practice. To address this contradiction, Gianina Druta approaches the reception of Ibsen in the Romanian theatre in the period 1894-1947, combining Digital Humanities and theatre historiography. This investigation of the European theatre culture and the way in which the foreign acting and staging traditions influenced the Romanian Ibsenites provides new insights into mechanisms of aesthetic transmission. Thus, this study presents a European theatre landscape whose unpredictability and uniqueness cannot be confined to essentialist interpretations.  afunded by Oslo Metropolitan University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCultural History. 4aDigital Humanities. 4aHistory of Theatre. 4aLiterature. 4aRomance Studies. 4aRomania. 4aSlavic Studies. 4aTheatre Studies. 4aTheatre and Performance. 4aTheatre. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aDigital Humanities.  aHistory of Theatre.  aLiterature.  aRomance Studies.  aRomania.  aSlavic Studies.  aTheatre Studies.  aTheatre and Performance.  aTheatre.2 aOslo Metropolitan Universityefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Complete eBook Package 2024z9783111332376oZDB-23-TGP40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839470183?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839470183zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/